metadata.name: Sixty# #29
metadata.description:
This idea was born from recent discussion on generative art and the path the medium is finding for itself. The project aims to take aesthetic concepts from sci fi graphic novels and blend them with generative systems of abstraction. 

The debate is between using previously established art forms to influence this new medium, or using a new medium to meticulously reproduce a previous medium. I believe thereâ€™s room to explore the full spectrum, and I am attempting to find the midpoint that fits my work and brings me the most happiness.

The title describes the eventual aesthetic objective, which is to create a piece which might look like a splash page a colorist alone has been given the freedom to design and explore their own specialty. It explores centralized polar compositions, vibrant colors, plus lots and lots of movement. 60# paper is a standard weight for printing of comic books and graphic novels.

Press â€™sâ€™ in live view to save a .png

Created with p5.js and chroma.js

metadata.name: Glass Ceiling v1.0 #50
metadata.description:
Toying with ideas combining form and movement, perhaps the last of my works containing only spherical shapes for a while. I will be visiting other parts of my mind for inspiration after this piece.

Sharing royalties with THREE.js (thanks for the great library) and Girls Who Code (we need more)!

Extremely rare to get 8 glass spheres... By the randomness imposed, 30% will have one sphere, 30% two, 20% three, 10% four, 5% five, 3.5% six, 1% seven and 0.5% eight. Happy hunting!

Interactive with several user controls:

With the mouse:

Left click and drag to change the viewing angle
Right click and drag to change the view center
Mouse wheel to change the distance to the view center

With the keyboard:

Keys "," and "." (i.e. "<" and ">") change the rotation speed left or right. You can stop it entirely, or speed it up to what I consider a reasonable maximum, rotating to the left or to the right. Each time you press, it adjusts the rotation speed.

metadata.name: E R E B U S #181
metadata.description:
Fragments of minds

Our daily life is filled with automatisms, habits that make our comfort zone. Then one day an event occurs that touches us deeply. We step out of our comfort zone, an internal emotional tornado is unleashed in our consciousness. This work tries to illustrate this flow of passion, this emotional violence on the fabric of daily life.

About features.
There are 3 random characteristics:

1. Latent state of mind
This feature correspond to the lines in the background. â€˜Healthyâ€™ is the most frequent, and the other types appear more rarely (â€™Psychoticâ€™ is really rare).

2. Crystallization

This feature corresponds to the strength of the flow of the passion in our mind. Probability : â€˜Normalâ€™ = 77%, â€˜Strongâ€™ = 33%.

3. Disturbance
The disturbance rate is â€™Lowâ€™ (frequent), or â€˜Highâ€™ (rare).

When a work is collected, a process of synchronicity is triggered. Synchronicity is a process of randomness that allows us to communicate with our unconscious (psychological paradigm) or with the hidden forces of the universe (spiritual paradigm). The rarer an image is, the more it represents an exceptional psychic state.

To print a high resolution image (resolution is 6400*6400px.), press [p].
To print a screen resolution image, right-clic then â€˜save imageâ€™.

This artwork celebrate the anniversary of FxHash - Happy Birthday little baby :-)
50% of primary sales are donate to the Processing Foundation (thank you for making my days better).

Artwork by @GenerativePunk.

metadata.name: a pale reflection #12
metadata.description:
a canvas is prepared; grids and vignette applied.

marks are added (or not)

a drawing method is chosen

the drawing method is iterated, resulting in a heavily stippled image

the image is sent to a shader

various maths occur inside the shader

the resulting shaded image is then given a border

and thus to the screen

a pale reflection - original music here: https://rtsixty.bandcamp.com/track/pale-reflection 
listen while waiting to be signed.

99.9% of royalties to original minter.

metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #309
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: Lost in the attraction / abstraction #71
metadata.description:
This project is an experiment with a chaotic attractor, radial symmetry and some Perlin noise.

---
Features

Parts: the number of symmetrical parts (4|6|8|10)

Palette: the palette chosen to draw the sketch

Attractors incrementation: a number between 0.0013 and 0.003 which will increment the parameters (a, b, c & d) of an attractor (Clifford A. Pickover).

---
Resolutions & controls

By default the work is drawn on a canvas of 1280 x 1280 pixels but you can double or triple this resolution, for this in live mode add to the URL &scale= with the desired factor.

You can also download an image (PNG) by pressing [d] key.


---
This artwork celebrate the first anniversary of FxHash, 50% of the proceeds will go to the Processing Foundation.


Created with typescript and simplex-noise (npm package). 

Artwork by Nicolas Lebrun / @nclslbn / https://nicolas-lebrun.fr/contact/

metadata.name: Nullteilung #109
metadata.description:
Nullteilung is another exercise in suprematism and composition. Born from a series of exercises in subdevision and tesselation, it seeks to connect with the user through the creation of a sense of order and balance in the composition.

The term "Nullteilung" a German word that can be translated to "zero division" which is suggesative of the order and disorder paramount in the piece, working toward a goal of emotional and programmatic purity.

metadata.name: Holiday Snowfall #17
metadata.description:
This piece was created to simulate the peaceful experience of viewing snowfall against a minimalist mountain scene. The probability of creating a new snowflake is randomly determined in each frame by the snowflakeProbability value. The mountain shapes are randomly drawn on the canvas using bezierVertex functions and the skies also lerp between day and night shades to simulate the passing of time.

This program is meant to bring a touch of winter magic to your screen and help you celebrate the holidays with wonder. Its minimalist design and peaceful atmosphere are intended to bring a smile to your face and help you embrace the beauty of the season. I hope you enjoy this free mint as a small token of appreciation for the fx(hash) community and all that fx(hash) has achieved this year. Happy holidays!

Made by wandurz using p5.js
December, 2022

metadata.name: Space & Ego #83
metadata.description:
In 1934, German philosopher Max Bense published his first work â€œRaum und Ichâ€ (Space & Ego) where he explored the concept of â€˜information aestheticsâ€™, proposing that the aesthetic value of an artwork could be derived from its underlying informational structure. 

Bense asserted that "Space" extends beyond physical dimensions into the realm of abstract ideas, mathematical possibilities, and the unseen information shaping an artwork, while acknowledging its potential, boundaries, and prospects.

The term "ego," usually associated with an artist's subjective impulses and emotional idiosyncrasies, is redefined in Bense's framework. As technology and information theory become integrated into artistic creation, the artist's role changes from a subjective creator to an architect of information and systems.

Thirty years later Manfred Mohr, an abstract expressionist, discovered Bense's information aesthetics in early 60â€™s, and his artistic thinking changed radically. Within a few years, his art transformed to computer generated algorithmic geometry. A pioneer of generative art, Mohr relentlessly explored precise geometric forms, symmetry, and a mathematical approach to art. 

While Benseâ€™s work continues to provide a philosophical foundation and conceptual framework for generative art, Mohr demonstrated the power of computational processes to produce intellectually engaging artworks. The series 'Space & Ego' pays homage to both Bense and Mohr while initiating a dialogue. 

Rooted in Mohr's concept of a random point within a square, this series broadens the "space" made possible by evolution of generative art. While the plotters of the 1960s were confined to monochromatic outputs, I have experimented with palettes uncommon in plotter projects. My choice of colors was expressive and more in tradition with abstract expressionists of 1960s. 

A random point is selected within a square, and the four resulting polygons are filled with lines. The probability of these polygons being filled with lines follows four approaches, ascending and descending from top-left to bottom-right (and vice versa), and radial expansion outward (and vice versa). All works can be plotted and have been designed for a precise fill of colors within the polygons. 

Implemented in JS, this code utilizes the Perlin.js and Simple-noise.js libraries.

Press p to save a PNG of the image in full screen. Press s to save a single complete SVG file for plotting. 

And this is a redeemable project in case youâ€™d like to receive a physical plot! 

Pixel Love!

objkt.name: Wisdom Tiles from the Old Country #3

metadata.name: Wisdom Tiles from the Old Country #3
metadata.description:
In the Netherlands we have a tradition that just won't go away. It's the Delft's Blue porcelain wisdom tiles. These tiles are a frumpy reminder of folk wisdom passed down through the generations. 
Most grandparents have at least 3x of them. 

Today we love to give these as an ironic joke present to friends at a housewarming party. We then hang these at a prominent place, like our toilet, so family and guests can be inspired by the wisdom of oldentimes while doing the business.

It's literally wisdom for you to poop on. 

For this I've taken this tradition and given it a modern twist. I collected all the elements: walls, tiles, Delfts Blue patterns*, countless dutch proverbs, cut them up, sprinkled with icons, made some tweaks for added humor, put it all in a blender, and turned that dial to 11. 

*For the Delfts Blue designs, I took inspiration not just from Dutch culture, but also from Keltic, Polynesian, and Heavy Metal / Punk. It adds much needed diversity and it fits perfectly.

The end result is the NFT collection you see here.

I hear you asking: Hey @Platolstoy: These new mixed-up proverbs, what do they mean? 
Answer: Well, that's up to you, really. What do you want it to mean? 

Most of the elements in the layers were sourced from Midjourney, designed in Photoshop, composited in After Effects, and last but not least generated with @PureSpider's PFP Token generator.

This project is a layered composition consisting of:
65x Backgrounds of different walls
27x Tiles of different materials
36x Delfts Blauw* patterns
86x Cheesy proverbs 2x lines
66x Icons

In total: literally a million-gazillion unique combinations of Wisdom Tiles. (1000 ed)
Feel free to explore and choose one that fits your look on life.

Have a nice day! 
Plastic Tolstoy / @platolstoy / https://plastictolstoy.com/
